yesterday I went through old photos. & today i journaled about it. 

to explain: my journal prompt today was “what do you need to forgive yourself for?”

& my answer was how I grieved the death of my mom. Or tbh.. lack there of. I was only 19. I didn’t want it to be real. I still don’t want it to be real. So I just never acknowledged it. I never let myself think about it or her. I never participated in the funeral planning bc I couldn’t look at pictures. I was never home bc her absence hurt me. So I just moved on, moved away from home, and never looked back. 

I never processed what it was like to lose my mom. And with-in a year I, too, became a mom to twins. Burying those feelings even deeper inside me to avoid any discomfort.. I never grieved my loss. 

Now at 28 years old, it haunts me. The emotions I never let myself feel. The tears, the anger, the heartbreak.. & now it seeps in when I least expect it & it makes me feel weak & embarrassed. I’ve done so much work on myself- which has been such a double edged sword.. because while I am starting to discover who I am and why I am the way I am, it doesn’t come without extreme discomfort to feel what I have buried & ignored for so long. 

But today I am deciding that there is no right or wrong way to grieve. I forgive myself for what I did or did not do. Because I’m tired of pretending everything’s fine & I’m fine. I have almost 10 years of pent up grief & anger & sadness and I’m ready to allow myself to feel it all. The good & bad. 

So here’s the photos I was once too scared to look at for fear of what it may stir up🫶🏼

summer of ‘23🌤️🌴🥥✨

by far my favorite! I’ve always said the happiest I’ve ever been was the summer of 2018. When it was just me, jake, & the twins living in KC. No dogs or baby Jett yet. Life was easy & we spent every single day at a baseball game or by the pool with Uncle Harry @hilbutera 🤣

That was the last summer I ever really did the whole “baseball” thing. After that I was pregnant & hated to travel. Then a newborn. Then Covid. Then boom my kids were in school & it was easier to just stay home. (My baseball season motto has always been “If I’m gonna be miserable, I’d rather be miserable in my own home”). 

But this year I decided to say f*ck it bc who knows how much longer we have to do this whole baseball thing. We got to see daddy pig more times this season than in the past few years combined.. & it’s not even over yet 🤪 

Couldn’t have done it all w/o @aubrianaeve ! She made all the solo & family trips possible. And now cheers to all 3 kids being in school full time & us doing absolutely nothing to celebrate 🫶🏼
